Massachusetts General Laws c. 186, \u00a.proposition: Massachusetts General Laws c. 186, § 14 provides that tenants are entitled to the covenant of quiet enjoyment, which prohibits landlords from interfering with tenants’ use and enjoyment of their rental units.

c. 93A.proposition: This Court has jurisdiction over this matter pursuant to Massachusetts General Laws c. 186, § 14, c. 93A, and other applicable statutes.

(M.G.L. c. 186, \u00a7 14).proposition: CAUSE OF ACTION: BREACH OF THE COVENANT OF QUIET ENJOYMENT (M.G.L. c. 186, § 14)

M.G.L. c. 186, \u00a7 14.proposition: Pursuant to M.G.L. c. 186, § 14, Plaintiff is entitled to recover actual damages, three times the amount of actual damages due to the Defendant’s willful conduct, and reasonable attorney’s fees and costs.
